{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651756"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:27:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:27:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18490"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18490"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.79,0,0.04,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11219"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112968"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11219"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95000"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6993"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26326"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112968"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe venous drainage of the midgut follows a specific pattern that corresponds to its arterial supply and embryological development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the venous drainage of the midgut?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drains into multiple small veins that empty into the azygos system","Drains into the superior mesenteric vein","Drains into the left renal vein","Drains into the superior vena cava via multiple tributaries","Drains directly into the inferior vena cava"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe venous drainage of the midgut is into the \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior mesenteric vein, \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich in turn joins the splenic vein to form the portal vein to form the portal vein. The superior mesenteric vein receives tributaries from the small intestine, caecum, appendix, ascending colon, and proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into multiple small veins that empty into the azygos system\u003C/strong\u003E - The azygos system primarily drains the thoracic and abdominal walls, not the gastrointestinal tract\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into the left renal vein\u003C/strong\u003E - The renal veins drain the kidneys, not the gastrointestinal tract\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into the superior vena cava via multiple tributaries\u003C/strong\u003E - The superior vena cava drains the upper body, not abdominal organs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains directly into the inferior vena cava\u003C/strong\u003E - The midgut venous drainage must first pass through the portal system and liver\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis venous drainage pattern ensures that nutrients absorbed from the midgut pass through the liver via the portal system for processing before entering the systemic circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superior mesenteric vein drains blood from the midgut, which extends from the duodenum to the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon.","The superior mesenteric vein joins with the splenic vein to form the portal vein.","Blood from the midgut must pass through the portal system and liver before entering systemic circulation."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95000"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18490"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95000"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T17:21:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T17:21:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11219"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112968"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"}